{
  "texts": [
    "Accordingly, the growing usage of technology in the teaching and learning process has shifted the landscape of education around the world.",
    "This, in turn, creates gaps in the concepts of traditional learning and necessitates the use and application of new approaches to stay relevant.",
    "The theory of connectivism, which was first introduced by Siemens (2005) and developed by Downes (2005 Downes (, 2012)), aims to fill in the gaps in the present day.",
    "According to Siemens (2005), connectivism constitutes the assumption that students should integrate ideas, theories, and general knowledge in an effective way.",
    "It acknowledges that technology plays a significant role in education and that staying connected all the time allows us to make decisions about how we learn."
  ]
}